{
  "\ufeff1. Which anticoagulant acts by chelating calcium ions and is most commonly used for complete blood count (CBC)?\nA. Heparin\nB. EDTA\nC. Sodium fluoride\nD. Oxalate\nAnswer: B. EDTA\n\n2. In spectrophotometry, optical density (OD) is directly related to:\nA. Transmittance\nB. Absorbance\nC. Wavelength\nD. Refractive index\nAnswer: B. Absorbance\n\n3. Which change occurs in blood if serum is not separated promptly after collection?\nA. Increase in glucose\nB. Decrease in potassium\nC. Decrease in glucose\nD. Increase in sodium\nAnswer: C. Decrease in glucose\n\n4. During electrophoresis at alkaline pH, which plasma protein migrates fastest toward the anode?\nA. Gamma globulin\nB. Alpha globulin\nC. Albumin\nD. Fibrinogen\nAnswer: C. Albumin\n\n5. Which component of a spectrophotometer selects a specific wavelength of light?\nA. Detector\nB. Cuvette\nC. Monochromator\nD. Amplifier\nAnswer: C. Monochromator\n\n6. Which hormone promotes glycogen synthesis in the liver?\nA. Glucagon\nB. Insulin\nC. Cortisol\nD. Adrenaline\nAnswer: B. Insulin\n\n7. The major metabolic abnormality in uncontrolled diabetes mellitus is:\nA. Persistent hypoglycemia\nB. Increased insulin secretion\nC. Hyperglycemia due to impaired glucose utilization\nD. Increased glycogen storage\nAnswer: C. Hyperglycemia due to impaired glucose utilization\n\n8. Enzymes lower the activation energy of a reaction by:\nA. Increasing substrate concentration\nB. Changing equilibrium constant\nC. Providing an alternative reaction pathway\nD. Increasing temperature\nAnswer: C. Providing an alternative reaction pathway\n\n9. Which enzyme is most specific for liver cell injury?\nA. ALP\nB. ACP\nC. ALT (GPT)\nD. Amylase\nAnswer: C. ALT (GPT)\n\n10. A patient with obstructive jaundice is most likely to show increased levels of:\nA. ALT only\nB. Amylase only\nC. Alkaline phosphatase\nD. Creatinine\nAnswer: C. Alkaline phosphatase\n\n11. HDL is considered protective against coronary artery disease because it:\nA. Delivers cholesterol to tissues\nB. Increases triglycerides\nC. Removes excess cholesterol from tissues\nD. Produces cholesterol\nAnswer: C. Removes excess cholesterol from tissues\n\n12. Which electrolyte is primarily responsible for maintaining extracellular osmotic pressure?\nA. Potassium\nB. Calcium\nC. Sodium\nD. Magnesium\nAnswer: C. Sodium\n\n13. Creatinine is formed from the metabolism of:\nA. Glycogen\nB. Creatine phosphate\nC. Cholesterol\nD. Uric acid\nAnswer: B. Creatine phosphate\n\n14. The principle of flame photometry is based on measurement of:\nA. Absorbed light\nB. Reflected light\nC. Emitted light from excited atoms\nD. Scattered light\nAnswer: C. Emitted light from excited atoms\n\n15. Which step of PCR requires the highest temperature?\nA. Extension\nB. Annealing\nC. Denaturation\nD. Hybridization\nAnswer: C. Denaturation\n\n16. A standard graph in biochemical estimation is prepared primarily to:\nA. Determine pH\nB. Calculate unknown concentration from absorbance\nC. Store quality-control data\nD. Measure reaction time\nAnswer: B. Calculate unknown concentration from absorbance\n\n17. Hyperuricemia is most commonly associated with:\nA. Gout\nB. Diabetes mellitus\nC. Hepatitis\nD. Anemia\nAnswer: A. Gout\n\n18. Which plasma protein fraction contains most antibodies?\nA. Albumin\nB. Alpha globulin\nC. Beta globulin\nD. Gamma globulin\nAnswer: D. Gamma globulin\n\n19. A control serum result repeatedly above the acceptable range indicates:\nA. Random error only\nB. Systematic error\nC. No error\nD. Sample contamination only\nAnswer: B. Systematic error\n\n20. According to Beer-Lambert's law, if the concentration of a solution is doubled while path length remains constant, the absorbance will:\nA. Be halved\nB. Remain unchanged\nC. Double\nD. Become zero\nAnswer: C. Double\n21.The primary site of hematopoiesis in a healthy adult is:\nA. Liver\nB. Spleen\nC. Red bone marrow\nD. Lymph nodes\nAnswer: C. Red bone marrow\n\n22. Which hormone primarily regulates erythropoiesis?\nA. Insulin\nB. Erythropoietin\nC. Thyroxine\nD. Cortisol\nAnswer: B. Erythropoietin\n\n23. Erythropoietin is produced mainly by the:\nA. Liver\nB. Spleen\nC. Kidney\nD. Bone marrow\nAnswer: C. Kidney\n\n24. The normal adult hemoglobin that constitutes the largest proportion of total hemoglobin is:\nA. HbA\u2082\nB. HbF\nC. HbA\nD. HbS\nAnswer: C. HbA\n\n25. Sickle cell disease results from the presence of:\nA. HbA\u2082\nB. HbF\nC. HbS\nD. HbH\nAnswer: C. HbS\n\n26. \u03b2-thalassemia is characterized by:\nA. Defective globin chain synthesis\nB. Defective heme synthesis\nC. Increased platelet production\nD. Increased erythropoietin production\nAnswer: A. Defective globin chain synthesis\n\n27. Which blood index is calculated by dividing PCV by RBC count?\nA. MCH\nB. MCHC\nC. MCV\nD. RDW\nAnswer: C. MCV\n\n28. A patient with iron deficiency anemia typically shows:\nA. Macrocytic hypochromic cells\nB. Normocytic normochromic cells\nC. Microcytic hypochromic cells\nD. Spherocytes\nAnswer: C. Microcytic hypochromic cells\n\n29. Polycythemia refers to:\nA. Increased platelet count\nB. Increased WBC count\nC. Increased RBC mass\nD. Decreased hemoglobin\nAnswer: C. Increased RBC mass\n\n30. Which white blood cell is primarily responsible for antibody production?\nA. Neutrophil\nB. Monocyte\nC. B lymphocyte\nD. Eosinophil\nAnswer: C. B lymphocyte\n\n31. A marked increase in immature leukocytes in peripheral blood is most suggestive of:\nA. Anemia\nB. Leukemia\nC. Hemophilia\nD. Thalassemia\nAnswer: B. Leukemia\n\n32. The characteristic cell of chronic myeloid leukemia (CML) is associated with:\nA. Philadelphia chromosome\nB. Barr body\nC. Howell-Jolly body\nD. Heinz body\nAnswer: A. Philadelphia chromosome\n\n33. Which leukocyte is most commonly increased in parasitic infections?\nA. Basophil\nB. Neutrophil\nC. Eosinophil\nD. Monocyte\nAnswer: C. Eosinophil\n\n34. The first step in the coagulation cascade is:\nA. Formation of fibrin\nB. Activation of clotting factors\nC. Clot retraction\nD. Platelet destruction\nAnswer: B. Activation of clotting factors\n\n35. Prothrombin time (PT) is mainly used to assess:\nA. Intrinsic pathway\nB. Extrinsic pathway\nC. Platelet function only\nD. Fibrinolysis\nAnswer: B. Extrinsic pathway\n\n36. Activated Partial Thromboplastin Time (APTT) evaluates:\nA. Extrinsic pathway\nB. Common pathway only\nC. Intrinsic and common pathways\nD. Platelet count\nAnswer: C. Intrinsic and common pathways\n\n37. Hemophilia A results from deficiency of:\nA. Factor VIII\nB. Factor IX\nC. Factor V\nD. Factor XIII\nAnswer: A. Factor VIII\n\n38. Which anticoagulant acts by chelating calcium and is preferred for routine hematology?\nA. Heparin\nB. EDTA\nC. Citrate\nD. Oxalate\nAnswer: B. EDTA\n\n39. In flow cytometry, cells are primarily analyzed based on:\nA. Weight and density\nB. Electrical conductivity only\nC. Light scattering and fluorescence\nD. Hemoglobin concentration\nAnswer: C. Light scattering and fluorescence\n\n40. The ESR (Erythrocyte Sedimentation Rate) is generally increased in:\nA. Polycythemia\nB. Inflammatory conditions\nC. Spherocytosis\nD. Hemophilia\nAnswer: B. Inflammatory conditions\n41. Which structure is primarily responsible for maintaining the shape and rigidity of most bacteria?\nA. Capsule\nB. Cell membrane\nC. Cell wall\nD. Ribosome\nAnswer: C. Cell wall\n\n42. Bacteria arranged in grape-like clusters are termed:\nA. Streptococci\nB. Diplococci\nC. Staphylococci\nD. Tetrads\nAnswer: C. Staphylococci\n\n43. Which phase of the bacterial growth curve is characterized by rapid cell division?\nA. Lag phase\nB. Log (Exponential) phase\nC. Stationary phase\nD. Death phase\nAnswer: B. Log (Exponential) phase\n\n44. The primary purpose of Gram staining is to differentiate bacteria based on:\nA. Shape\nB. Motility\nC. Cell wall composition\nD. Capsule formation\nAnswer: C. Cell wall composition\n\n45. Which of the following is a selective medium for Gram-negative enteric bacteria?\nA. Blood agar\nB. Nutrient agar\nC. MacConkey agar\nD. Chocolate agar\nAnswer: C. MacConkey agar\n\n46. Autoclaving achieves sterilization by:\nA. Dry heat at 160\u00b0C\nB. Steam under pressure\nC. UV radiation\nD. Filtration\nAnswer: B. Steam under pressure\n\n47. The Kirby-Bauer method is used to determine:\nA. Bacterial count\nB. Antibiotic susceptibility\nC. Hemolysis\nD. Capsule formation\nAnswer: B. Antibiotic susceptibility\n\n48. Which bacterium is classically identified by acid-fast staining?\nA. Escherichia coli\nB. Staphylococcus aureus\nC. Mycobacterium tuberculosis\nD. Streptococcus pyogenes\nAnswer: C. Mycobacterium tuberculosis\n\n49. Normal flora of the large intestine predominantly consists of:\nA. Mycobacteria\nB. Anaerobic bacteria\nC. Spirochetes\nD. Rickettsiae\nAnswer: B. Anaerobic bacteria\n\n50. Which biosafety practice is most important when handling clinical specimens?\nA. Mouth pipetting\nB. Wearing PPE\nC. Keeping cultures open\nD. Eating in the laboratory\nAnswer: B. Wearing PPE\n\n51. Sabouraud Dextrose Agar (SDA) is primarily used for:\nA. Viral culture\nB. Fungal culture\nC. Mycobacterial culture\nD. Parasite culture\nAnswer: B. Fungal culture\n\n52. Dermatophytes commonly infect:\nA. Liver and spleen\nB. Brain and lungs\nC. Skin, hair and nails\nD. Blood and bone marrow\nAnswer: C. Skin, hair and nails\n\n53. Which clinical specimen is most appropriate for diagnosing tinea capitis?\nA. Urine\nB. Hair sample\nC. Blood\nD. Stool\nAnswer: B. Hair sample\n\n54. The multiplication of viruses can occur only:\nA. In culture media\nB. In distilled water\nC. Inside living host cells\nD. On nutrient agar\nAnswer: C. Inside living host cells\n\n55. ELISA used for HIV diagnosis primarily detects:\nA. RBC antigens\nB. Viral antigen and/or antibodies\nC. Fungal spores\nD. Platelet antibodies\nAnswer: B. Viral antigen and/or antibodies\n\n56. Western blot is mainly used in HIV testing to:\nA. Culture the virus\nB. Confirm positive screening results\nC. Count viral particles\nD. Determine antibiotic sensitivity\nAnswer: B. Confirm positive screening results\n\n57. A hapten is a substance that:\nA. Is always immunogenic by itself\nB. Cannot induce an immune response unless attached to a carrier protein\nC. Is a type of antibody\nD. Activates complement directly\nAnswer: B. Cannot induce an immune response unless attached to a carrier protein\n\n58. Which immunoglobulin is the first antibody produced during a primary immune response?\nA. IgA\nB. IgG\nC. IgM\nD. IgE\nAnswer: C. IgM\n\n59. The Mantoux test is used to detect:\nA. Typhoid fever\nB. Tuberculosis infection\nC. Brucellosis\nD. Rheumatoid arthritis\nAnswer: B. Tuberculosis infection\n\n60. Widal test is primarily used in the diagnosis of:\nA. Tuberculosis\nB. Typhoid fever\nC. Brucellosis\nD. Syphilis\nAnswer: B. Typhoid fever\n61. The primary purpose of fixation in histopathology is to:\nA. Increase staining reaction\nB. Preserve tissue structure by preventing autolysis and putrefaction\nC. Remove water from tissue\nD. Decalcify bone\nAnswer: B. Preserve tissue structure by preventing autolysis and putrefaction\n\n62. Zenker\u2019s fluid is classified as:\nA. Simple fixative\nB. Compound fixative\nC. Special stain\nD. Mounting medium\nAnswer: B. Compound fixative\n\n63. The main principle of Hematoxylin and Eosin (H&E) staining is:\nA. Lipid dissolution\nB. Acid-base interaction between dye and tissue components\nC. Fluorescence emission\nD. Enzyme activity\nAnswer: B. Acid-base interaction between dye and tissue components\n\n64. PAS stain is most useful for detection of:\nA. Calcium deposits\nB. Glycogen and basement membranes\nC. Iron pigments\nD. Acid-fast bacilli\nAnswer: B. Glycogen and basement membranes\n\n65. Histokinette is mainly used for:\nA. Staining blood films\nB. Automated tissue processing\nC. Decalcification of bone\nD. Smear preparation\nAnswer: B. Automated tissue processing\n\n66. The correct order of tissue processing is:\nA. Embedding \u2192 Fixation \u2192 Dehydration \u2192 Clearing\nB. Fixation \u2192 Dehydration \u2192 Clearing \u2192 Embedding\nC. Dehydration \u2192 Fixation \u2192 Clearing \u2192 Embedding\nD. Clearing \u2192 Embedding \u2192 Fixation \u2192 Dehydration\nAnswer: B. Fixation \u2192 Dehydration \u2192 Clearing \u2192 Embedding\n\n67. Cryostat microtome is used for:\nA. Paraffin sectioning\nB. Frozen section cutting\nC. Bone decalcification\nD. Smear staining\nAnswer: B. Frozen section cutting\n\n68. DPX in histopathology is used as:\nA. Fixative\nB. Mounting medium\nC. Decalcifying agent\nD. Stain\nAnswer: B. Mounting medium\n\n69. The main purpose of decalcification is to:\nA. Remove fat from tissue\nB. Remove calcium to allow sectioning of bone\nC. Preserve proteins\nD. Increase tissue hardness\nAnswer: B. Remove calcium to allow sectioning of bone\n\n70. In cytology, Papanicolaou stain is mainly used for:\nA. Bacterial culture\nB. Cervical cytology screening\nC. Blood grouping\nD. Parasite detection\nAnswer: B. Cervical cytology screening\n71. The term \u201cproximal\u201d in anatomical terminology refers to a structure that is:\nA. Away from the trunk\nB. Closer to the point of origin\nC. Below another structure\nD. Toward the midline\nAnswer: B. Closer to the point of origin\n\n72. Which component of blood is primarily responsible for oxygen transport?\nA. Plasma\nB. Platelets\nC. Red blood cells\nD. White blood cells\nAnswer: C. Red blood cells\n\n73. Hemoglobin binds oxygen reversibly through:\nA. Iron in heme group\nB. Globin protein only\nC. Plasma proteins\nD. Carbon dioxide\nAnswer: A. Iron in heme group\n\n74. The main function of the stomach is:\nA. Absorption of water\nB. Protein digestion and food storage\nC. Fat absorption\nD. Bile production\nAnswer: B. Protein digestion and food storage\n\n75. Which enzyme is responsible for starch digestion in the mouth?\nA. Pepsin\nB. Trypsin\nC. Salivary amylase\nD. Lipase\nAnswer: C. Salivary amylase\n\n76. The smallest functional unit of the kidney is:\nA. Nephron\nB. Neuron\nC. Alveolus\nD. Glomerulus\nAnswer: A. Nephron\n\n77. The primary function of the alveoli in the lungs is:\nA. Air filtration\nB. Gas exchange\nC. Mucus secretion\nD. Oxygen transport\nAnswer: B. Gas exchange\n\n78. Insulin is secreted by which part of the endocrine system?\nA. Thyroid gland\nB. Adrenal cortex\nC. Pancreatic \u03b2-cells\nD. Pituitary gland\nAnswer: C. Pancreatic \u03b2-cells\n\n79. Which chamber of the heart receives oxygenated blood from the lungs?\nA. Right atrium\nB. Right ventricle\nC. Left atrium\nD. Left ventricle\nAnswer: C. Left atrium\n\n80. The main function of the large intestine is:\nA. Protein digestion\nB. Absorption of water and electrolytes\nC. Secretion of enzymes\nD. Production of bile\nAnswer: B. Absorption of water and electrolytes\n81. The diagnostic stage of Entamoeba histolytica in stool is:\nA. Trophozoite only\nB. Cyst only\nC. Both cyst and trophozoite\nD. Larvae\nAnswer: C. Both cyst and trophozoite\n\n82. Giardia lamblia is primarily diagnosed in stool by identifying:\nA. Eggs\nB. Cysts and trophozoites\nC. Larvae\nD. Microfilaria\nAnswer: B. Cysts and trophozoites\n\n83. The infective stage of Plasmodium falciparum for humans is:\nA. Merozoite\nB. Sporozoite\nC. Gametocyte\nD. Schizont\nAnswer: B. Sporozoite\n\n84. The most commonly used concentration technique for stool examination is:\nA. Gram staining\nB. Formalin-ether sedimentation\nC. Acid-fast staining\nD. India ink method\nAnswer: B. Formalin-ether sedimentation\n\n85. The best sample for diagnosis of microfilaria is:\nA. Urine\nB. Morning sputum\nC. Peripheral blood collected at night\nD. Stool\nAnswer: C. Peripheral blood collected at night\n86. In a continuous flow analyzer, samples are processed:\nA. One by one in separate cuvettes\nB. In a continuous stream separated by air bubbles\nC. Only by centrifugation\nD. Manually by technician\nAnswer: B. In a continuous stream separated by air bubbles\n\n87. Discrete analyzers are characterized by:\nA. Continuous sample flow system\nB. Individual reaction cuvettes for each sample\nC. No use of reagents\nD. Only manual operation\nAnswer: B. Individual reaction cuvettes for each sample\n\n88. The main function of an ELISA reader is to:\nA. Count blood cells\nB. Measure absorbance of antigen-antibody reactions\nC. Separate plasma proteins\nD. Measure blood gas levels\nAnswer: B. Measure absorbance of antigen-antibody reactions\n\n89. Blood gas analyzers are primarily used to measure:\nA. Hemoglobin and RBC count\nB. pH, CO\u2082, and O\u2082 levels in blood\nC. Platelet function\nD. Serum cholesterol\nAnswer: B. pH, CO\u2082, and O\u2082 levels in blood\n\n90. A key feature of centrifugal analyzers is:\nA. Samples remain stationary\nB. Separation of reaction components by centrifugal force\nC. No use of reagents\nD. Manual pipetting of all samples\nAnswer: B. Separation of reaction components by centrifugal force\n91. The main principle of blood banking is based on:\nA. Enzyme activity in blood\nB. Antigen-antibody reactions\nC. Blood viscosity\nD. Plasma protein concentration\nAnswer: B. Antigen-antibody reactions\n\n92. The most important blood group system in transfusion practice is:\nA. Lewis system\nB. Kell system\nC. ABO system\nD. Duffy system\nAnswer: C. ABO system\n\n93. Which blood group is considered the universal donor (for RBC transfusion)?\nA. AB positive\nB. O negative\nC. A positive\nD. B negative\nAnswer: B. O negative\n\n94. The Rh factor is primarily associated with:\nA. Platelet antigen\nB. Red blood cell surface antigen D\nC. Plasma protein\nD. White blood cell antigen\nAnswer: B. Red blood cell surface antigen D\n\n95. Cross-matching is performed mainly to:\nA. Determine hemoglobin level\nB. Detect compatibility between donor and recipient blood\nC. Count RBCs\nD. Measure clotting time\nAnswer: B. Detect compatibility between donor and recipient blood\n96. The main aim of pathology in clinical diagnosis is to:\nA. Treat diseases directly\nB. Study disease causes and mechanisms for diagnosis\nC. Perform surgery\nD. Prescribe drugs\nAnswer: B. Study disease causes and mechanisms for diagnosis\n\n97. Reversible cell injury is most likely to recover when the cause is:\nA. Severe and permanent\nB. Mild or temporary\nC. Always infectious\nD. Genetic only\nAnswer: B. Mild or temporary\n\n98. Ischemia refers to:\nA. Increased blood flow to tissues\nB. Reduced blood supply to tissues\nC. Infection of tissues\nD. Fluid accumulation in tissues\nAnswer: B. Reduced blood supply to tissues\n\n99. A benign tumor is characterized by:\nA. Rapid metastasis\nB. Well-differentiated cells and slow growth\nC. Invasion of surrounding tissues\nD. High malignancy rate\nAnswer: B. Well-differentiated cells and slow growth\n\n100. A tumor marker is best defined as:\nA. A bacterial enzyme\nB. A substance produced by tumors or host in response to tumor\nC. A type of antibody only\nD. A staining reagent\nAnswer: B. A substance produced by tumors or host in response to tumor": null
}
